			<td colspan="6" class="DetailTitle" style="text-align:center;">
                            Summary on Grant Application Form</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailValue" style="padding:5px;">
                        <span id="lblAbstract">1)  The production of large area (10cm x 10cm) slabs of well characterised barium hexagonal ferrite, for use as free space isolators and circulators.  2)  To investigate the loss mechanisms in the material in the mm-wave region, using a variety of standard techniques.Progress:Barium hexagonal ferrite powder has been produced by co-precipitation of ferric oxide and barium oxide from an aqueous solution. The starting materials of barium chloride and ferric chloride, in the correct molar ratios, are dissolved to form an aqueous solution and the oxides precipitated using a solution of sodium hydroxide and sodium carbonate (1). The precipitates were filtered from the solution and thoroughly washed with distilled water to remove all traces of the sodium hydroxide/sodiium carbonate. The dried powders were fired at 1000C, to react the components and form the hexagonal ferrite phase. Samples of the powder have been analysed using X-ray powder diffraction techniques to determine the phase of the reacted material. Early experiments indicated the presence of other phases in the material, indicating a loss of barium. The problem arose due to the large quantities of powder required to produce the slab and the fact that the starting composition quoted (1) did not appear to scale to the larger quantities. Several experiments were carried out in order to determine the appropriate pH of the solution to give single phase material on fining. Good quality barium hexagonal ferrite is now being produced.  A large die has been constructed for the pressing of the powders into the form of slabs. The required amount of powder is loaded into the die and subjected to a pressure of ~200 tons. The pressed samples were removed from the die and fired at 1000 C to sinter the material. Problems have currently been encountered with the slabs cracking and warping during the sintering process and with excessive grain growth. The temperature distribution within the furnace will be investigated in order to improve the quality of the finished specimens, as well as using alumina slabs to maintain the shape of the specimens.  1)  Preparation of High-Coercivity Barium Hexaferrite, Koichi Haneda et al, Journal of the American Ceramic Society, Vol.57, No.8, 1974.</span>
                        </td>
		</tr>
